<exercise>
<statement><p>
In the sketch below of a three-dimensional curve and its osculating circle at a point, label <m>\hT</m> and <m>\hN</m>. Will <m>\hB</m> be pointing out of the paper towards the reader, or into the paper away from the reader?
</p><sidebyside width="40%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw[thick] plot[domain=0:5]({sin(\x r)},\x);
\draw(.707,2.36) node[vertex]{};
\draw[ultra thick, - \gt , red] (.71,2.36)--(.14,3.18);
\draw[ultra thick, - \gt , red] (.71,2.36)--(-.11,1.78);
\draw[dashed] (-1.414,.86) node[shape=circle, draw, minimum size=5.2cm]{};
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside></statement>
<hint><p>
	Use the right-hand rule to figure out how <m>\hB</m> is oriented.
</p></hint>
<answer><sidebyside width="40%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
	\draw[thick] plot[domain=0:5]({sin(\x r)},\x);
	\draw(.707,2.36) node[vertex]{};
	\draw[ultra thick, - \gt , red] (.71,2.36)--(.14,3.18) node[above right]{$\hT$};
	\draw[ultra thick, - \gt , red] (.71,2.36)--(-.11,1.78)node[below left]{$\hN$};
	\draw[dashed] (-1.414,.86) node[shape=circle, draw, minimum size=5.2cm]{};
	\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside><p>
<m>\hB</m> points out of the page (towards the reader).
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
	<m>\hT</m> is tangent to the curve, while <m>\hN</m> is perpendicular to it.
	</p><sidebyside width="40%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
		\draw[thick] plot[domain=0:5]({sin(\x r)},\x);
		\draw(.707,2.36) node[vertex]{};
		\draw[ultra thick, - \gt , red] (.71,2.36)--(.14,3.18) node[above right]{$\hT$};
		\draw[ultra thick, - \gt , red] (.71,2.36)--(-.11,1.78)node[below left]{$\hN$};
		\draw[dashed] (-1.414,.86) node[shape=circle, draw, minimum size=5.2cm]{};
		\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside><p>
	Using the right-hand rule and <m>\hB=\hT \times \hN</m>, 	<m>\hB</m> points out of the page (towards the reader).
</p>

<p>To see this, point the fingers of your right hand in the direction of <m>\hT</m>, and curl them inwards until they are in the direction of <m>\hN</m>. To do this, your thumb must be pointing towards you, not away from you. Your thumb shows the direction of <m>\hT \times \hN</m>.
</p></solution>
